{
  "title": "Agile Adoption Over Agile Transformation",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "72ce06b2d4e3a4df",
      "text": "The word transformation indicates moving from the current state to a new state, which is predicted in advance. This goes against the core philosophy of agility. Sunil Mundra says.\n\nCompanies that approach an Agile Transformation typically apply a traditional budgeting approach to such an endeavour, where the size, the scope and the goal are all defined upfront. All that for an endeavour that is novel to them, with a lot of remaining ambiguity around what change means to different people, and with the type of company change needed or beneficial that is still unknown.\n\nWhat works instead is an Agile Adoption, an open-ended endeavour adopting an Agile approach that can face the novelty, the ambiguity, the uncertainties and the unknowns in an effective and successful manner.\n\nAn Agile Adoption typically starts simple, proceed with an iterative and incremental approach, goes through a gradual learning process discovering what works and what not and how to adapt things to different contexts that exist in the organisation and to the way circumstances evolve in the organisation. It often starts bottom up before inviting the leaders' top-down drive and the middle managers in a middle-out approach."
    }
